observations.recommendation:
We recommended that the Municipal Mayor, in coordination with the Municipal Engineer, to:

Integrate the implementation of construction safety into the overall project cost under pay item “SPL: Construction Safety and Health” as a lump sum amount to be quantified in the detailed estimate;

Strictly require all contractors to ensure their entire workforce are wearing the required safety gear or personal protective equipment at all times within the construction project site for the protection and welfare of both the construction workers and the public at large;


Closely monitor the proper implementation of CHSP and standards by the contractors at the project sites by maintaining detailed records of non-compliance of the contractor per site visitation, which can be referenced during future payment processes; and

Formulate an internal policy that clearly defines the appropriate sanctions or penalties to be applied to contractors found in violation of the CHSP to ensure accountability and adherence to safety protocols.

We recommended that Management:

Instruct the Inventory Committee, together with the Municipal Assessor and Municipal Accountant, to ascertain the cost of the road lot component of each road network, if readily available.  Otherwise, the fair market value (assessed value) of the lot component shall be specified;

Direct the Municipal Accountant to:

Properly recognize the value of the lot component in the books of accounts and provide the depreciation cost for each depreciable road component;

Prepare a JEV to take up the proposed adjusting journal entries to correct the affected account balances;

Disclose the total Road Network System account in the Notes to Financial Statements;

Direct the Inventory Committee to use the proper format of the RPCLRN with complete details such as road ID, components, cost, and condition;

Direct the Municipal Engineer to provide the Municipal Accountant and the GSO with the complete description and cost segregation of road components for road projects; and

Require the Municipal Accountant and the GSO to keep a complete Local Road Network Ledger Card and Property Card for all roads and its components, respectively.

We recommended that Management:

Instruct the HRMO to require all current elective local officials to submit written manifestation if they opted not to avail of the mandatory leave so that it will be added to their accumulated leave benefits, otherwise, the same will be deducted from their earned leave benefits;

Require the Municipal Accountant to issue demand letters to former elective officials for the refund of excess payment of their terminal leave benefits;

Require the HRMO to furnish the Audit Team a complete set of leave cards of all officials and employees; and

Instruct the Municipal Treasurer to issue OR once refund was made by the concerned elective officials and furnish the Audit Team copy of said ORs.

We recommended that Management:

Instruct the HRMO to require all current elective local officials to submit written manifestation if they opted not to avail of the mandatory leave so that it will be added to their accumulated leave benefits, otherwise, the same will be deducted from their earned leave benefits;

Require the Municipal Accountant to issue demand letters to the three former elective officials for the refund of the excess payment of their terminal leave benefits;

Instruct the Municipal Treasurer to issue OR once refund was made by the concerned elective officials and furnish the Audit Team copy of said Ors

We recommended that Management:

Instruct the Municipal Engineer to prepare the Program of Works and Detailed Quantity and Cost Estimates separately in which the standard forms of DPWH shall be adopted;

Require the BAC Secretariat to properly and completely prepare the bidding documents to conform with the nature and requirements;

Instruct all BAC members to prepare and approve the Abstract of Bids as Calculated after the evaluation of bids;

Require the BAC Secretariat to submit all the minutes of Bid Evaluation and the corresponding attendance sheets;

Require the BAC to ensure that the contracts are approved within 10 days from the receipt of Notice of Award by the winning bidder;

Instruct the BAC to post the Notice of Award in the PhilGEPS website within the prescribed period;

Instruct the BAC to ensure that Notices to Proceed are issued within the prescribed period from the date of approval of the pertinent contracts;

Direct the BAC to ensure that winning bidders comply with all the requirements set forth under 2016 Revised IRR of RA No. 9184 such as the posting of surety bonds callable upon demand as performance and warranty security duly certified by the Insurance Commission before the awarding and signing of the contract; and

Require the Municipal Accountant, in coordination with the BAC and Municipal Engineer, to submit the lacking documents to the Audit Team for further verification.

We, therefore, recommended that the Municipal Accountant:

Reclassify all completed projects from Construction in Progress accounts to their appropriate PPE accounts and consequently compute depreciation from the date of completion;

Exert extra effort to trace and verify the status and history of the Construction in Progress accounts included in the beginning balances and take the appropriate action if verified completed;

Book up as “School Building” the two completed projects pertaining to construction of school building (Bacnor National High School and Malasin Elementary School) with a total contract cost ₱1,479,934.84 and recognize the appropriate amount of depreciation; 

Book up as “CIP-Infrastructure Assets” the on-going project regarding the construction of public market at barangay San Antonino which is 15.59 percent completed with a contract cost of ₱498,099.19; 

Adjust the recorded amount of CIP pertaining to the seven on-going projects to coincide with the percentage of completion vis-à-vis the contract cost; and

Coordinate with the Engineering Office to establish a reporting mechanism on the status of on-going constructions-in-progress and completed projects to prevent delays in recognition of the same to their appropriate accounts and to recognize the same even in the event of non-availability of actual billings from contractors.

Considering that our previous recommendations were not complied with, the Audit Team reiterated its recommendations that the Local Chief Executive direct the Accountable Officers to:

Observe the proper conduct of physical count to come up with a complete and reliable Report of Physical Count of Property, Plant and Equipment;

Prepare and maintain Property Cards for all the agency properties and reconcile with the Property, Plant and Equipment Ledger Cards of the Accounting Office;

Prepare the required reports such as Inventory Count Form, Physical Inventory Plan (PIP), and List of Non-existing/missing PPEs;

Undertake the disposal proceedings and derecognize unserviceable properties from the accounting books and property records upon disposal thereof based on the approved IIRUP; and

Pursue the one-time cleansing of PPE accounts in accordance with COA Circular No. 2020-006 dated January 31, 2020 to finally establish PPE balances that are verifiable as to existence, condition and accountability.

We recommended that Management:
Require the Inventory Committee to:
Conduct a thorough and complete physical inventory of all properties owned by the agency at least once a year;
Submit the RPCPPE to the Audit Team not later than January 31 of each year;
Instruct the Municipal Accountant to:
Coordinate with the Inventory Committee to reconcile PPE ledger cards with the result of the physical count by PPE classification and immediately make the necessary adjustments, in case of detection of errors, duly supported with complete documentation;
Make the necessary adjustments in the books to correct the accounting errors on the misclassification of some PPE items and non-derecognition of items already distributed to end-users, to reflect the correct balances of the affected accounts in the financial statements; and
Initiate the compliance with the guidelines and procedures for the One-Time Cleansing of PPE account balances to reconcile PPE accounts and establish PPE balances that are verifiable as to existence, condition and accountability.

We recommended that Management require the Municipal Accountant to:
Require the contractors of the three completed infrastructure projects to submit valid financial instruments equivalent to the retention money totaling ₱619,890.06 with a validity period of one year from the date of issuance of the Certificates of Completion;
Deduct the 10 percent retention money equivalent to 50 percent of the value of works amounting to ₱722,768.62 from the next progress billing for the Construction of Level III Water Supply;
Subject initial progress payments exceeding 50 percent of the works and one-time payments for 100 percent completion to retention money equivalent to at least 10 percent of the 50 percent of the value of the completed work for projects that are satisfactorily undertaken and on schedule; otherwise, impose additional retention money on the remaining progress payments equivalent to 10 percent;
Require the contractors to submit a valid financial instrument equivalent to the retention money deducted from their progress payments in case they request its substitution which will only be accepted if the project is on schedule and satisfactorily undertaken; and
Release the retention money to contractors upon final acceptance of the project.

We recommended that Management:
Enhance Solid Waste Management Awareness by conducting proactive IECs such as seminars, trainings, and forums supported by informative and visually-engaging signages placed in strategic locations, and the effective use of social media platforms for wider information dissemination. Coordination with Barangay Solid Waste Management Committees and academic institutions is also encouraged to maximize outreach and impact;
Implement clear guidelines to enforce waste segregation at source, such as instituting a policy of non-collection for unsegregated waste and establishing additional MRFs to adequately handle recyclable waste across all barangays;
Incorporate the procurement of another hauling vehicle in the Projects/Programs and Activities of the Municipality and/or expedite the repair of the currently unserviceable garbage truck to improve waste collection; and
Expand the scope of garbage collection services to ensure regular and equitable coverage of all barangays within the Municipality.

In view of the foregoing, we recommended that Management oversee the adherence to the pertinent provisions of NGAS Manual for LGUs and applicable policies and guidelines on the accounting and management of inventory to ensure the reliability and fair presentation of the balances in the financial statements.
In particular, we recommended that Management direct:
The Municipal Accountant to institute measures to ensure that inventory items received as donation are properly recorded and accounted for in the books;
The Inventory Committee to undertake physical inventory every six months, as required by the Manual, and submit the RPCI in order to ascertain the correctness of the inventory;
The GSO to properly maintain and update stock cards for all inventory items, to facilitate the review, physical count, and reconciliation of inventories. Likewise, prepare the RIS and SSMI, to be used as basis for recording the expenditure in the books; and
The Municipal Health Officer and heads of other all concerned department who are receiving goods-in-kind from National Government Agencies or from any source, to inform and coordinate with the GSO of such goods, before issuance to the concerned department or end-user. The GSO shall thereafter furnish the accounting department the necessary documents on the receipt and issuance for proper recording in the books of accounts.

Considering that our previous recommendations on the same issue were not complied with, the Audit Team reiterated its recommendation that the Local Chief Executive direct the Accountable Officers to:
Observe the proper conduct of physical count to come up with a complete and reliable Report of Physical Count of Property, Plant and Equipment;
Prepare and maintain Property Cards for all the agency properties and reconcile with the Property, Plant and Equipment Ledger Cards of the Accounting Office;
Prepare the required reports such as Inventory Count Form, Physical Inventory Plan (PIP), and List of Non-existing/missing PPEs;
Undertake the disposal proceedings and derecognize unserviceable properties from the accounting books and property records upon disposal thereof based on the approved IIRUP; and
Pursue the one-time cleansing of PPE accounts in accordance with COA Circular No. 2020-006 dated January 31, 2020 to finally establish PPE balances that are verifiable as to existence, condition and accountability.

We, therefore, recommended that the Local Chief Executive install and implement a sound internal control system concerning cash collections and deposits by:

strictly ensuring compliance with the receipt and collection process outlined in Book II, Chapter III, Section 86 of the Local Treasury Operations Manual; 

directing all the collecting officers to remit religiously their collections to the Municipal Treasurer daily; 

requiring the Municipal Treasurer to maintain a record of accountable forms being issued to each collecting officer and monitor its status daily to avoid the recurrence of the same event and in compliance with Book II, Chapter III, Section 86 of the Local Treasury Operations Manual; 

establishing proper accountability in the receipt, issuance, and monitoring of accountable forms to prevent error, theft, fraud, misuse, or misappropriation; and

necessitating that the cashbook balance must be reconciled with the cash on hand at the close of each day and with the subsidiary ledgers at least once every quarter.

We recommended that the Municipal Mayor:

Require the HRMO to assess the existing Organizational Structure so that the ideal number of plantilla personnel will be established and submit a report with recommendations thereon to the Local Chief Executive;

Create clear-cut policies and guidelines to address the issue on the necessity and propriety of hiring JOs taking into consideration the existing regular employees;

Comply with the existing daily minimum wage rate for Region VIII, as prescribed by the RTWPB;

Require the Municipal Accountant to process only payrolls with complete documentary requirements.

We recommended that the Municipal Mayor, being the HoPE, to:
Mandate the PE to utilize the standard rates regarding the cost of issuance of a complete set of bidding documents to maximize its proceeds from such sale, thereby providing additional fund for the payment of the BAC honoraria;
Direct the BAC to ensure that the results of the bidding procurement at hand are well documented and signed by the appropriate officials who possess the necessary authority and responsibility for the outcome of the bidding;
Instruct the BAC Secretariat to post the NOA and any issued Supplemental/Bid bulletins within the prescribed period to promote transparency, efficiency and accountability in the procurement process;
Comply with the prescribed period for issuing NOA to prevent delays in project implementation, facilitating timely delivery and completion of projects, thereby enabling constituents to access and enjoy the benefits derived from these projects at an earlier stage;
Direct the BAC Secretariat to post the NOA in the PhilGEPS website within the prescribed period;
Instruct the BAC Chairman to see to it that prior to contract signing of infrastructure projects, require the winning bidder to submit the following:
Performance Security to ascertain the legality and validity of contracts entered into by the Municipal Government, thereby ensuring transparency and accountability in procurement practices; and
CSHP approved by DOLE to ensure the protection and welfare of both the construction workers and the general public.
Enter into a contract with the bidder with LCRQ immediately from the receipt of the NOA, and submission of all relevant documentary requirements to ensure timely implementation of projects, thereby enabling constituents to promptly benefit from them; and
Comply the prescribed period of issuing NTP to streamline the overall project implementation process, hence preventing any potential delays in the completion of projects, which enable the constituents of timely access of the intended benefits of these projects.

