We recommended that the Municipal Mayor direct the Municipal Accountant to:

reclassify the balances recorded as Accounts Payable to the appropriate account as defined in Annex B of COA Circular No. 2015-009 or the Revised Chart of Accounts for LGUs;

trace prior years balances of accounts payable and the correctness of accounting entries on its recognition and settlement, and make the appropriate journal entry, as necessary;

maintain Subsidiary Ledgers for each payee/creditor which should be reconciled with the balance in the General Ledger; and

stop the practice of recording accounts payable without complete supporting documents. Henceforth, JEV on the recognition of payables should be supported with complete documents to prove validity, correctness, and existence of the claims.

We recommended that the Local Chief Executive, being the Chairman of the Local School Board:

a)	continue to convene for an early review and approval of the SEF Budget;


b)	direct the Municipal Budget Officer to assist the LSB in reviewing SEF budget to identify the proper PPAs for appropriation; 


c)	instruct the BAC to properly plan and schedule all procurement activities pertaining to educational projects for their timely implementation; and 


d)	direct the Local School Board to be aware of their responsibilities and functions and convene regularly to address issues and concerns for a better public education.

We recommended that the Management:

convene earlier with the LSB for the timely review and approval of the SEF Budget to avoid delays in the implementation of the PPAs under the said fund; 

direct the Municipal Budget Officer to assist the LSB in reviewing SEF budget particularly in the coming up with a more specific and detailed PPAs for appropriation; 

instruct the Bid and Awards Committee to properly plan and schedule all procurement activities pertaining to educational projects for their timely implementation; and

direct the Municipal Accountant to review claims and their supporting documents before effecting payment.

We recommended that Management:
a. Require the Municipal Engineer to provide the Municipal Accountant and ICO-General Services Officer (GSO) with the complete description and cost segregation of road components for road projects, taking also into account the allocation of the cost incurred for consolidated road projects to each road network comprising thereof based on the Program of Works;
b. Instruct the Municipal Agriculturist as head of the Appraisal Committee to evaluate and determine the fair value of road networks and its components with no available cost but were identified in the inventory count for proper recording in the books;
c. Require the Municipal Engineer, in coordination with the Inventory Committee, to determine the road projects which structures or components were already replaced to facilitate the derecognition of the carrying amount of the assets replaced;
d. Require the ICO-GSO as head of the Inventory Committee for Road Networks to observe the format required in the preparation of RPCLRN; and
e. Direct the ICO-GSO to prepare annually the Report on Local Road Network and keep a complete Local Road Network Property Card for all roads and its components using the prescribed form.

We recommended that the Management strengthens its monitoring controls by requiring the Accounting, MSWD, CDRRM, RHU Office, and Mayor’s Offices to:

a. Ensure proper coordination among the Offices concerning the receipt and distribution of Donations In-Kind;

b. Ensure issuance of Acknowledgment Receipts to all future receipts of donations in-kind to confirm that donations are properly recorded and accounted for and; 

c. Ensure that all future issuances of donated items are properly supported with Issuance Form for In-Kind Donations or any document/record to prove receipt by and distribution to the intended beneficiaries; and

d. Determine the inventory of remaining undistributed items for recording in the Registry of Donated Relief Goods for DRRM.

We recommended that the Management:

a. Directs the BAC Secretariat to update themselves to the laws, rules and regulations on government procurement, and;

b. Directs the Municipal Accountant to ensure that all disbursement vouchers relating to government procurement are adequately supported with mandatory documentary requirements before processing the payments.

We recommended that the Management:

a. Appoints an eligible and computer literate as one of the members of the BAC to comply with the posting requirements on all its procurement and; 

b. Posts the Notices of Award and to Proceed, and the approved contract be posted in the PhilGEPS website and website of the municipality, if any, within the reglementary period as required by the 2016 Revised IRR of R.A. No. 9184.

We recommended that the procuring entity strictly adhere to the pertinent provisions of the 2016 Revised Implementing Rules and Regulations to ensure transparency and accountability in the procurement process. We specifically recommended that Management instruct: 
The Bids and Awards Committee (BAC) comply with the submission of the Final APP to the GPPB on or before the end of January of the budget year and it shall be posted in the GPPB Website to ensure transparency in the procurement process and in the implementation of procurement contracts;
The BAC comply with the posting requirement of the Approved Bidding Documents to ensure timely dissemination of the procurement opportunity; 
The BAC adopt the required procedures and conditions in the Post-Qualification stage particularly in the verification, validation and ascertainment of all statements made and documents submitted by the bidder with the Lowest Calculated Bid to ensure that they are in accordance with the requirements as stated in the Bidding Documents;
The BAC to ensure that the required performance security is posted by the winning before the signing of the contract to guarantee the faithful performance of his obligations under the contract; and
The BAC, through its Secretariat, see to it that the Notice of Award, Notice to Proceed and a copy of the approved contract were posted in the PhilGEPS website within three and fifteen calendar days from their respective issuances for  information and  transparency in the procurement process.

We recommended that the Management:

require suppliers to submit their mayor’s or business permit, tax returns, OSS and all other documents as required by law and meticulously examine their legal, technical and financial capacity;

stop entering into contracts with suppliers whose line of business/industry is not within the scope of the subject transaction;

ensure that the contracts/purchase orders contain the required warranty clause;

accept only duly executed Omnibus Sworn Statements containing all the required declarations; and

comply with the online posting requirement for transparency and accountability.

We recommended that Management:
a. Require the Municipal Accountant to trace from the pertinent accounting records all completed public infrastructure projects of the LGU under Flood Control Systems, Parks, Plazas and Monuments and Other Infrastructure Assets accounts and have these reconciled with the records of the Municipal Engineer and ICO-GSO to accurately determine the detailed composition of said accounts and the relative completion dates;
b. Upon determination of said public infrastructure projects, instruct the Municipal Engineer, in coordination with the ICO-GSO, to determine the estimated useful life thereof based on the experience of the agency with similar assets and submit the same to the Municipal Accountant;
c. Require the Municipal Accountant to prepare the necessary adjusting journal entries to record the accumulated depreciation for said public infrastructure accounts using the useful life provided by the Municipal Engineer; and
d. Require the Municipal Accountant to provide for the additional current year depreciation for the Improvement of Burgos Municipal Water System Level III in the amount of ₱238,113.16 by debiting Depreciation-Infrastructure Assets and crediting Accumulated Depreciation-Water Supply Systems.

We recommended that Management:
a. Require the Municipal Accountant to verify the subsidiary account with a negative balance for possible overpayment;
b. Instruct the Municipal Treasurer to require the payees whose check payments became stale and could no longer be found to submit their Sworn Statements pertaining thereto, and immediately request the bank for stop payment of the checks and request for a certification for non-negotiation of the checks;
c. Require the Municipal Accountant to further review the composition of the Accounts Payable account to determine the claims supported with complete and proper documentation; and
d. Instruct the Municipal Budget Officer to revert all claims which are not valid to the unappropriated surplus of the General Fund and SEF.
e. Require the Municipal Accountant to reclassify the payables amounting to ₱3,293.43 and ₱325.00 to Due to GSIS and Due to BIR accounts, respectively.

We recommended that Management instruct the MSWDO to:
a. Submit the photocopies of valid IDs of all beneficiaries with their specimen signatures or, in lieu thereof, the Barangay Certification with their specimen signatures;
b. Submit the valid IDs with specimen signatures for subsidy releases to persons other than the beneficiary and authorization letter if they were not the alternative representative of the family head allowed by the DSWD during payout;
c. Require the Punong Barangays to issue certificates of eligibility for the recipients who were not included in the original list of eligible recipients and those who replaced the original beneficiaries that have already refunded their cash subsidies in order to establish their eligibility to receive SAP and submit the same to the Audit Team for further evaluation;
d. Submit the revised cash assistance payrolls which are not yet signed by the recipients, free of any alterations and duly signed by the Municipal Mayor and MSWDO; and
e. Submit the lacking SAC forms or those forms with noted deficiencies duly signed by the Punong Barangay and MSWDO.

We recommended that Management:
a. Instruct the Municipal Engineer to prepare the Program of Works and Detailed Quantity and Cost Estimates separately in which the standard forms of DPWH may be adopted;
b. Require the BAC Secretariat to properly and completely prepare the bidding documents to suit the nature and requirements of each procurement activity leaving no blank spaces, options and notes/instructions;
c. Instruct the BAC to require the winning bidders to fully accomplish and update the Special Conditions of the Contracts, and submit the same, as revised, to the Audit Team;
d. Instruct all BAC members to prepare and approve the Abstract of Bids as Read and Abstract of Bids as Calculated right after the examination and evaluation of bids, respectively;
e. Require the BAC Secretariat to submit all the minutes of Bid Evaluation and the corresponding attendance sheets;
f. Instruct the BAC-TWG to observe strictly the guidelines in the conduct and preparation of Bid Evaluation and Post-Qualification Reports to establish properly the eligibility of the participating bidders;
g. Instruct the BAC to prepare BAC Resolution Adopting and Confirming the TWG Detailed Bid Evaluation Report and Declaring the LCB, and BAC Resolution Adopting and Confirming the TWG Post-Qualification Evaluation Report and Declaring the LCRB in the conduct of Public Bidding;
h. Require the BAC to ensure that the contracts are approved within 10 days from the receipt of Notice of Award by the winning bidder;
i. Instruct the BAC to post the Notice of Award and Notice to Proceed in the PhilGEPS website within the prescribed period; and
j. Require the Municipal Accountant, in coordination with the BAC and Municipal Engineer, to submit the lacking documents to the Audit Team for further verification, technical evaluation and inspection.

We recommended that Management:
a. Instruct all department heads to properly and comprehensively plan their procurement activities, and to include in their PPMPs all items needed by their office or planned programs, projects and activities for the year 2021 in order to avoid or minimize the revisions of the consolidated APP and to strategize the quarterly procurement of similar items without resorting to piecemeal purchases;
b. Require the BAC to use the PPMP format provided by the GPPB in order to disclose all the needed information;
c. Require the BAC Secretariat to consolidate and update the APP every time changes are proposed thereto; and
d. Instruct the BAC to submit the BAC resolutions recommending the use of alternative method for procurements without specific method or with changes to the method of procurement in the PPMP or APP.

We recommended that Management:
a. Require the personnel assigned in waste collection and dumpsite to maintain basic records to monitor daily waste collection, transfer, disposal and special occurrences such as fire, accidents, spills unauthorized loads and daily waste inspection logs;
b. Instruct the SWMO-Designate to ensure that personnel directly dealing with collection of solid waste are provided with personal protective equipment and paraphernalia;
c. Require the personnel assigned in the operation of the sanitary landfill and his family members to vacate the area immediately to avoid being exposed to the harmful effects of wastes being disposed thereat;
d. Instruct the SWMO-Designate to include in its proposed PPAs for the year 2021 the construction of a toilet facility for the use of personnel assigned in the operations of the sanitary landfill and MRF; and
e. Likewise, instruct the SWMO-Designate to propose the inclusion in the agreement with the Junk Shop a specific provision that all waste pickers and sorters are registered under said private entity, if augmentation of the LGU workforce assigned in waste sorting or segregation is still not viable, in order to discourage the authorization of scavengers in the area; and
f. Instruct the SWMO-Designate to determine further the steps to be undertaken which may include allocation of funds or generation of additional revenues, coordination with the component barangays and law enforcers, or partnership with private sector or NGOs to support the full implementation of the comprehensive SWM plan, and in the strict imposition of penalties against persons committing the prohibited acts provided in Section 48 of RA No. 9003 and the grant of incentives to those actively participating in the waste management efforts of the LGU.

We recommended that the Local Chief Executive:

a.	create a team/committee to conduct an immediate physical count of all its property, plant and equipment. They are required to submit the RPCPPE on or before January 31 of each year, copy furnished the COA Auditor concerned pursuant to Section 266 of GAM for LGUs, Volume I;

b.	require the committee to check the conditions of all LGU properties. Any damage, obsolete and unserviceable property shall be reported in the Inventory and Inspection Report of Unserviceable Property (IIRUP) and Waste Materials Report and immediately request for disposal, if any. Lastly, the inventory reports should be reconciled with the accounting records to determine the correctness of the property records;

c.	require each Department Head to conduct every year a physical inventory count of all properties under their office and to submit inventory report to the inventory committee for the random validation of the existence of the property; and

d.	require both the Accountant and General Services Office to maintain and update records and ledgers of all properties owned by the LGU pursuant to Section 269, Volume I of GAM for LGUs.

We recommended to the Management  the following:

The Municipal Assessor to furnish the Municipal Treasurer the assessment roll, together with a list of assessed real property indicating the names of the concerned taxpayers in whose name the property is declared and assessed during the period.  The said list shall include information such as but not limited to the following: (1) Name of RPT/SET taxpayer and complete address; (2) Descriptions of the assessed property;  (3) Tax Declaration Number;  (4) Market Value; (5) Assessed Value; (6) Type of Property, Estimated Useful Life (if applicable); and (7) Actual Use of Property;

The Municipal Treasurer to provide the Municipal Accountant a summary copy of her collections for the year showing the details: (1) Name of RPT/SET taxpayer and complete address; (2) Tax Declaration Number; (3) Total Amount Paid; (4) Detailed Breakdown/Explanation of Actual Amount Paid; and (5) a duly certified list showing the name of taxpayers and the amount due and collectible for the year.  Likewise, prepare and furnish the Municipal Accountant the list of taxpayers with delinquencies for the years 2004 to 2018 as of December 31, 2019 to support the year-end ledger balances;

