We recommended that the Municipal Mayor:
require the Municipal Assessor to furnish the Municipal Treasurer the assessment roll, together with a list of assessed real property indicating the names of the concerned taxpayers in whose name the property is declared and assessed during the period.  The said list shall include information such as but not limited to the following: (1) Name of RPT/SET taxpayer and complete address; (2) Descriptions of the assessed property;  (3) Tax Declaration Number;  (4) Market Value; (5) Assessed Value; (6) Type of Property, Estimated Useful Life (if applicable); and (7) Actual Use of Property;
require the Municipal Treasurer to provide the Municipal Accountant a summary copy of his collections for 2017 showing the details: (1) Name of RPT/SET taxpayer and complete address; (2) Tax Declaration Number; (3) Total Amount Paid; (4) Detailed Breakdown/Explanation of Actual Amount Paid; and (5) a duly certified list showing the name of taxpayers and the amount due and collectible for the year.  Likewise, prepare and furnish the Municipal Accountant the list of taxpayers with delinquencies for the years 2002 to 2017 as of December 31, 2017 to support the year-end ledger balances;
instruct the Municipal Accountant to prepare the necessary adjustments of RPT/SET Receivables once the list of delinquent taxpayers is received from the Municipal Treasurer to reflect the correct balance of these receivable accounts. Likewise, maintain and update the corresponding subsidiary ledger for each taxpayer to facilitate monitoring and preparation of necessary reports/schedules.
direct the Municipal Accountant and the Municipal Treasurer to reconcile the schedule of delinquent RPT/SET taxpayers so that the latter could notify delinquent taxpayers on time.
prepare a statement of the reason or reasons for such non-collection or non-payment and submit to the Sanggunian concerned together with the list of taxpayers with delinquencies with a request for assistance in the enforcement of the remedies for collection provided in RA No. 7160 in order for the Municipality to have funds for other projects that will benefit its constituents.

We  have recommended the following:

a.	To ensure the success of the inventory committee, all heads of offices are advised to instruct their staff to cooperate in the conduct of physical count;

b.	Invite a representative of the Auditor to witness the inventory taking;

c.	Require the  Property Unit and the Accounting Office to maintain  complete and accurate Property Cards (PCs) and Property, Plant and Equipment Ledger Card (PPELC), respectively;

d.	Require the reconciliation of Property and Accounting records after the physical count;

e.	Require the submission of the Report on the Physical Count of Property, Plant and Equipment to the Property Unit and the COA office for verification and reconciliation of the results of physical count with the complete PPELC and PCs maintained by the Accounting Office and the Property Unit respectively;

f.	Require the Municipal Assessor and the Municipal Treasurer to work for the transfer of the Tax Declaration of the 14-hectare land  in the name of the municipality;

g.	Require the posting of property tag/number on the prominent portion of every movable non expendable property/equipment, and

h.	Make proper disposal of unserviceable property.

We have recommended that management  require   its officials and employees to settle their cash advances within the prescribed period as follows:

Cash   advances   for   local   travels   should   be  liquidated  within  30  days  from   return to official station;

Cash  advances  for  current  operating expenditures should be liquidated after the conclusion of the activity/occasion;

Excess cash advances should be refunded immediately, and

No  cash  advance  shall  be  allowed  unless  the  previous  cash advance is  first settled.

In order to rectify the foregoing deficiencies, we have recommended that:

a. the BAC Chairman  instruct the heads of requisitioning offices to avoid indicating the brand name of items being requested in the Purchase Request and the BAC Secretariat in the Request for Quotation, except for replacement of parts of equipment.  Instead, indicate the complete specifications of the items; 

b. the Bids and Awards Committee (BAC) Chairman   require the BAC Secretariat to post the Notice of Award in the Philgeps and website of the procuring entity within three (3) calendar days from its issuance and the Notice to Proceed and awarded contracts within fifteen (15) calendar days from issuance of the Notice to Proceed;

c.   management  require future contractors to submit duly accomplished performance security with a validity period that include the one year defects liability period pursuant to Section 39 of the RIRR of RA 9184. The validity period shall commence from the effectivity of the contract up to after one year from date of completion of the project or until the issuance of the Certificate of Acceptance.  Moreover, the Municipal Accountant being the internal auditor of the municipality should see to it that all supporting documents of disbursement vouchers are properly accomplished to ensure validity and legality of the transactions;

d.  management  require all future contractors to post warranty security after the defects liability period of one year from project completion.  Such security must be in accordance with the schedules prescribed in Sections 62.2.3.2 and 62.2.3.3 of the  RIIR of RA 9184, and

the Municipal Mayor  instruct the BAC Chairman to require future contractors to submit Construction Safety and Health Program approved by DOLE as attachment to the contract.  Moreover, the Acting Municipal Accountant should not process claims for infrastructure projects without the aforecited document.

While we recognize the ongoing efforts of the municipality, we have recommended that in order to enjoy the benefits of effective Ecological Solid Waste Management and to avoid possible sanctions, the members of the Municipal Solid Waste Management Board:

Facilitate any revision of the SWMP;
Ensure the completion of the sanitary landfill; 
Enforce waste segregation at source; and 
Monitor and encourage utmost compliance by its component barangays.

We have recommended to the Local Chief Executive the following:
a. Instruct the Accounting and Inventory Committee to undertake immediate preparation and submission of matrix of reconciliation of the physical inventory report of CY 2016 with that of the accounting records;
b. Require the Property Custodian and the Municipal Accountant to maintain complete and updated property and subsidiary records in conformity with Sections 119 and 120, Volume I of the MNGAS for LGUs;
c. Exhaust all possible means to document the legality of ownership over the 16 parcels of land through a Certificate of Title in the name of the Municipal Government of Burgos in conformity with Section 39 of PD 1445; and
d. Instruct the management to coordinate with concerned municipal officials in the documentation and processing of documents, which, if accomplished, is vital in the determination of the proper valuation or appraised value of the acquired lots.

We have recommended to the Local Chief Executive the following:
a. Submit all the required documents immediately to facilitate the conduct of contract review and to establish the regularity of the transaction;
b. Strict compliance with COA Circular No. 2009-001, COA Circular 2012-001 and Revised Implementing Rules and Regulations (IRR) of RA 9184 must be observed;
c. That the amount of retention money which was not deducted be substituted with any security in the form of irrevocable standby letter of credit from a commercial bank, bank guarantee or surety bond callable on demand for each progress billing made by the contractor;
d. That the 10% retention money shall be strictly imposed on every progress billing to be made by the contractor on the succeeding contracts entered into by the agency;
e. Instruct the BAC Committee to require the Contractor to post warranty security in favor of the Agency to cover structural defects and failures that may occur during the one (1) year period from the date of released of the 10% retention money; and
f. Instruct the BAC Committee to only issue a Certificate of Final Acceptance upon the lapsed of one (1) year from the date of project completion in conformity with the Revised Implementing Rules and Regulations (IRR) of RA 9184.

We have recommended to the Local Chief Executive the following:
a. Ensure that only allowable rates of travel expenses be claimed and if situation cannot be avoided that permits the employee to claim more than the allowed rate, a certification of the same should be given, provided that the most advantageous to the government from the standpoint of economy and efficiency should always be observed;
b. The amount of P16,602.00 representing claimed travelling expenses and per diems in excess of the allowable rates and P20,052.00 representing rebooking fee should be refunded;
c. Only permanent employees of the Municipality be allowed to attend trainings/seminars in order not to place the government in a disadvantageous position which may result to future loss;
d. Instruct the Municipal Accountant to perform internal audit functions such as to review the validity of the claim and the completeness of supporting documents before the preparation of disbursement vouchers as mandated under RA 7160 as powers and duties of the same; and
e. Instruct the concerned employees to give justifications on the need to conduct the Refresher Course outside the premises of the Municipality and to refund the amount of P3,600.00 representing per diems claimed by the On-the-Job Training students.

We have recommended that Management:
require the Municipal Treasurer to continue and intensify/improve their collection strategies on taxes due and collectible by sending RPTOP's and notice of delinquency to taxpayers and forming committee to conduct an information dissemination regarding the importance of paying taxes promptly and the consequences of non-payment of taxes and
if circumstances warrant, impose the provisions of Sections 258 and 260 of the Local Government Code of 1991 in the collections of delinquent taxes to satisfy taxes, penalties and costs with the following:
1. Seizure of personal property of the taxpayer and sale thereof at public auction;
2. File civil suit with the proper court; and
3. Levy on real property and sale of delinquent property or a usable portion thereof at public auction.

We recommended that management ensure that Gender and Development activities to be undertaken are aligned with the GAD Plan and that disbursements related thereto are supported with complete documentation. 

Accordingly, the following documents must be submitted to prove the validity of the disbursement for medical allowance/assistance amounting to P175,000.00:
an explanation for granting medical allowance/assistance of P2,500.00 each to the 70 LGU officials and employees instead of providing anti-flu/pneumonia vaccination as indicated in the Annual GAD Plan and Budget for FY 2016;
proof that the medical allowance/assistance was intended for the anti-flu/pneumonia vaccination of the recipients and that the same was actually used for that purpose; 
proof that the three officials and employees who did not affix their signatures in the payroll actually received their medical allowance/assistance totaling P7,500.00 each; 
written authority issued by the five officials and employees for their representatives to receive their medical allowance/assistance totaling P12,500.00 on their behalf; and

Otherwise, the said disbursement may be suspended or disallowed in audit.

